 :burn-in period: n. 1. A factory test designed to catch systems with
{marginal} components before they get out the door; the theory is that
burn-in will protect customers by outwaiting the steepest part of the
{bathtub curve} (see {infant mortality}). 2. A period of indeterminate length
in which a person using a computer is so intensely involved in his project
that he forgets basic needs such as food, drink, sleep, etc. Warning:
Excessive burn-in can lead to burn-out. see {hack mode}, {larval stage}.